segments.text: The history of planning in Fort Worth.
March 15th, interviewer Lance Freeman interviewing Emil R. Montsevice, senior planner in urban design, the planning department, the city of Fort Worth.
Okay, Mr. Montsevice, I wondered if you could please give us a brief biographical sketch of your life in planning, especially, and how you got to where you are right now.
Okay, I graduated from Texas A&M with a
And bachelors of architecture degree in 1966.
Went to City Council town for three years.
And got back out and went back and did a master's in turbine and regional planning in 1970.
Graduated back in 1971.
Came to work for the city of Fort Worth in 71.
Worked for two years for the city of Fort Worth as an associate planner.
And then I went to work for the city of El Paso as a senior planner for up until 1981.
Then I came back as a senior planner to work for the city of Fort Worth.
And that's where I am now, involved with design, urban design, and also company planning.
I have a staff of about

six planners that are responsible for, you know, comprehensive plans for the city, responsible for reviewing the flats, zoning cases, and I also work with another section of the planning department in terms of implementing urban design projects in areas where we may have federal funds to develop those type of projects to help the community.
Generally, that's where I am at this point.
OK.
Going back all the way to the history, when was the first legislative authorization of a comprehensive plan in your community?
I was looking at some of the history.
It was part of the Bartholomew plan that was done in 1927.
generally probably would be to take.
There was a Keshav plan done prior to that in 1909, but that was more of a part-time rather than a comprehensive plan.
Do you see any effects today from that Bartholomew plan?
I could not.
Do you?
OK. Is there, number three, is there any systematic periodic review of your city's comprehensive plan?

Yes, we generally, we did comprehensive planning, we did what we call a major comprehensive plan back in the early 70s, and it was undertaken by developing a number of sectors within the communities, generally about 11 sectors.
What we did, we

We sent out flyers and got people interested in coming to talk about their city and the plans for the future growth and development of the community and set up a committee and that particular committee had their own members and they worked with us.
We developed base information, developed a plan, went out and talked to them about it, show them what the effects were and so forth and worked on it.
generally on probably on a biweekly basis having meetings by doing the analysis and bringing that information, showing what it meant, and going back to them, coming up with a plan, working with them.
So that was the way it was set up.
And again, about two years ago, 1981, again we went through the same process of doing that and used the same type of system setting up a
sector planning process and working with the citizens, trying to solicit people of different concerns such as homeowners, developers, economists.
And try to have really everybody's input into this process and trying to have a basis for a plan.
So you had a different plan for each sector.
Right.
And then you combined all of those.
Right.
That is our comprehensive plan.
OK.
Presently, when Bob, I don't know, do you want to get into the present right now?
Yes, why not?
Presently, we're involved in the center.
We've just finished that process.
It's what we call a sector process.
But we're also getting involved in what we call district planning.
That's the outlined areas that are sort of where most of the new development is going on.
And we're hoping to develop a plan for that area.
But that will probably not entail so much input from citizen participation because, again, in those areas, there's really
but not that much population.
So what we're really looking at is what development has occurred and what has caused that development.
And we're trying to more or less look in an area in terms of what
man-made and natural elements to tell you what a piece of property can be utilized for and trying to come up with different alternatives for different pieces of property.
You might have, for example, an area that could have a commercial use or it could have an industrial use.
ETJ, extraterritorial jurisdiction, but it also includes
parts of the community that are in the city is a combination of both.

But what we're trying to do is be more realistic in terms of the market out there to try to say what really what land can be used for and then develop these different what we call scenarios or alternatives.
So one particular scenario

begins in that area then that should end up being a plan for that particular area and it'll sort of change everything else you know what i'm saying in other words okay rather than being adamant and saying well we're going to make this you know typically all plans have always shown everything single family you know just about but what we're really looking at is from the site planning board is what would really work and what would be the highest and best
Okay.
Have you been using any computer models in developing these plants?
Not necessarily these plants, but we have used the computer model in the study that we did for the Southwest Corridor,
analysis of the southwest freeway, in other words, where it should go and why it should go that way.
Okay, so mostly transportation.
Yeah, what kind of problems would we encounter on all our other major arterial systems.
Has your community's comprehensive plan ever been revised?
And if so, how does this revision take place?
Okay.
What we're trying to start out now is to revise our plan, what we call ongoing planning.
Once a major new development comes into an area that has changed the plan completely, we go back and look and reanalyze.
And we're trying to do this on a continuing basis rather than, say, every 10 years.
Rather than be static.
to continue to be in motion in terms of changing with the times.
And that's the way we're approaching it.
So even the plans that we had done in the last two years, we've come back and looked at some other areas and made changes to the original plan that we did simply to keep up with what's going on.
OK.

And most, well I won't say most, but many of these changes are really initiated by, again, development in the community, the market, what's happening in the private sector, you know, that causes this type of thing.

I'll take one of the biggest things to point out here for instance that the final decision to go with the Southwest Freeway alignment has caused some major changes in that area in terms of land use and the proposed zoning and land use.
for the plants that were there previously.
So we've really made a major change in all that area.
Okay.
Down to question number seven.
What administrative procedures and planning program elements does your community have for implementing community plans?
That's probably no different than any other community in that you've got a zoning commission and a planning commission.

We received a class and some cases that come through the system here and we revise and review those and look at it in terms of the comprehensive plan that we have developed and make a judgment in terms of, you know, is this good or bad for the plan or what are some of the problems with it or what are the good things about it.
We also have another section which is more
implementation section of the planning department that is involved with the federal programs, which get more planning on the neighborhood level, I would say.
And we're looking at the comprehensive plan that we've done for those areas.
Their work is a little more detailed in this aspect.
And what we try to do is when we get zoning cases or thoughts
We look at it in terms of what are those detailed plans for those areas and does it fit, you know, the overall plan for that community.
In other words, is it going against what the basic goals of the area are in terms of the development for the area?
Is it going to be positive or negative?
We use that many times.
In zoning cases where we want to make a point where we see there might be a detriment to the area if there's an intrusion of commercial or
industrial into a residential area.
Okay, good.
Our department is basically related directly to who worked for the zoning commission and also the city of Fort Worth had a zoning commission and a planning commission.
They're two different commissions.
Generally in Texas you have one with P and Z, but for some reason Fort Worth wanted to be a little bit...
We work directly for those two commissions.
We make reviews of zoning cases and those staff reports go to the zoning commission and we make a general discussion about the case for the positive and negative aspects of the zoning request.
We do.

work on being directed for the Planning Commission and that we review all the clats and make a judgment in terms of what we think might be some of the problems with the clats and what changes we need to take.
We look at it in terms of how those clats fit in with our National Territory Plan and that information is given over to the Planning Commission.
Who makes up these commissions?
Are they the citizens?
The commissions are appointed by city council members.
Generally what we have, and this was instituted probably about a year ago, where each particular board would have nine members.
So each councilman and each mayor would have one vote to appoint somebody on these boards.
It seems to be people representation for the community.
Is there a city manager in Fort Worth?
Yes, there's a city manager.
Our director, plane director, is the, you know, I was supervised by the assistant city manager, who is, again, supervised by the city manager.
So that's the order.
City manager, assistant city manager, plane department, and ourselves.
But again, we relay the record to these two boards and our responsibility to them.
If they are requesting certain studies or something, they can request it.
They don't have to go to the city manager and request the city manager to .
They go straight to you.
Yeah, .
OK. Let's go back to question number nine.
How many professional planners does your city employ now?
And could you please break them up into their groups?
Actually, we have generally two sections.
One, again, is the advanced planning, which is more involved with comprehensive planning and urban design.
And we have the other section, which is implementation planning, which is more involved with federal programs such as Community Development Block Grant, UDAGS.
I can't even think of this other program called
It's a jobs program that they have.
I couldn't think of the name of it.
But they're more related to social programs and implementation programs from an economic point of view and jobs programs.
Whereas the other department, the advanced planning, has to do with it.
No, they're the same section.
This is the planning department.
We have two sections.
One would be the advanced planning.
And advanced planning would be more of the physical aspects?
Yeah, the comprehensive planning part.
In our section, advanced planning, we have approximately, let's say, six, seven,
10 people, I'm going to say 11 people involved with comprehensive planning.
That includes transportation planners, two transportation planners, six or seven comprehensive planners, and of course, one assistant director, and of course, the general director.
On the other side, with the implementation planners, they're talking down the data services section.
housing section and economic section.
Housing and economic section and then they have the jobs section.
The jobs section has three people and they're involved with developing programs in terms of the federal funds that are used for jobs and they're working on programs in that aspect of it.
The other section is more involved with housing and redevelopment, economic redevelopment of areas.
They have approximately, let's see, they have six people working for them.
Of course, data services, they have about six people working for them.
And basically, data services involve crunching numbers.
OK.

What relation, going back to question number 10, I don't think we've hit upon your relationship to the legislative body, if any, and also to citizens groups besides at the planning commission meetings.
Our relationship with the legislative body is really, in terms of technical,
We are at their meetings, and if there's any questions in terms of some of the reports that we have put together, we answer them.
They really deal directly with the city manager, the city council.
In terms of citizen groups, like I said before, we set up this sector planning process.
We do have different committees in these sectors.
Our responsibility is to meet with them on a monthly basis, ones that are active.
Not all of them are active.
And we go out there and show them what zoning cases are coming about, what plans are happening, to keep them up to date with what's going on.
to make them aware of what the situation is in terms of the market.

And also if there's special studies to be done or there's a request for special studies, and again it comes back to our director from these citizen groups, and then we go ahead and either do the study or whatever the end of it is.
That's really the basic relationship.
They're basically a group that we work with as the committees, sector committees, sector councils.
So, in effect, they're almost like miniature planning and zoning commissions, not having the...
They don't have the authority.
We don't try to make them to have the authority.
It's more in terms of infiling them what's going on.
And there's many times that we're on a different side of the fence than they are.
There's a number of times that we're on the same side of the fence as the developer.
Because they have their local interests and you try to incorporate the city's interests.
Right.

And we looked at it from a planner standpoint which generally in some cases is different than a lot of the citizens because really I think if the citizens had their right they'd want everything to be single family.
They wouldn't want change but
I mean, that's what planning's all about in development, is change.
Okay, there was a city fair or exposition that you mentioned.
The city fair, I think, was in the early 30s.
It was promoted by Anglin Carter, which is a well-known individual of the community that had plenty of money and helped to initiate a lot of
This city fair took place generally in what is now called the Will Rogers Coliseum area, which includes a number of
museums such as the Amon Carter Museum, the Fort Worth Art Museum, the Kimball Art Museum.
Also Casa Manana is located in that area.
So it really sort of was the basis and stimulated that particular area in terms of arts and culture.
Okay.
How did the

development of the city charter play a role in the planning history and or any of the changes some of the changes uh city of fort worth basically have a cumulative type ordinance where generally if you have a zone a heavier zone such as commercial or industrial you can accumulate all the other zones in it such as
I could put a single-family in a commercial area, or I could put a multi-family in a commercial area, or I could put a commercial area in an industrial area.
And what we went through about two years ago was the review of the city ordinance to try to make certain recommendations, again, to the zoning commission, which in turn made it
their recommendations to city council in terms of changes.
And the thing that we were trying to get away from was to eliminate the accumulative aspects of our zoning ordinance.
It did pass, but only in terms of a moratorium until 1987.
It'll happen then.
In other words, if he had property right now, up until 1987, he just took and did all these things to it.
But after 1987, then it doesn't matter what your property is.
Once it's zoned, that's the way it's going to be.
Was there any particular reason why 87 was chosen?
No.
It's a political reason.
I mean, it was just a compromise for what the zoning

task force wanted was which was the group body again we had people from different departments city departments on there and also had some private citizens on there what we wanted to do was to really not just go ahead and do it right away but through the political process and the pressures from the
development industry, they got it to get it to extend that, so.
Okay.
That basically was the reason for that.
All right.
And I am the current staff.
Okay, Mr. Mountsvice, what has been the role of outside consultants in the city planning in Fort Worth?
Okay, since I've been here in the last three years, we've done the
A downtown plan by a consultant was costing $128,000.
This was done at Johnson Johnson in Roy.
Previously, most of our downtown plans were done by outside consultants in the early 70s.
I would say in terms of the downtown, the outside consultants have had a major influence on the development of the community and the growth of the downtown area.
is what is the current status of planning in your city?
We are in the process.
We just completed what we call the sector planning to update our comprehensive plan.
But we're also extending to what we call our district areas, which is more of the
of the community, and it's the area that includes the ETJ, the Charitable Jurisdiction, and City Limits, one and the same.
I mean, not one and the same, but it includes both those areas.
And it's more of the areas that are newly developing.
And what we're trying to do is, again, develop a comprehensive plan of the area.
So we can combine that with the second plan and have an overall comprehensive plan for the community.

We're doing that a little differently, but we're looking at each particular area and trying to come up with more or less highest and best use, but also have category of uses for a particular area, rather than saying that it should be only used for one particular purpose.
We're in the process of doing all that now.
And you've mentioned some political influences affecting planning in the community.
Can you categorize that?
Well, I say politically from a standpoint that generally,

The comments that are made by our staff in terms of zoning requests and changes are not adhered to that closely, and I would think generally politically, the reason is the political influence that is happening to the city council and also probably to the zoning commission.
In fact, the zoning commission here about a year ago
much more pro the government.
They pretty well rubber-stamped everything.
But here lately, with new changes to the board, it has improved.
So we're seeing much more, how shall I say, they're relating more to what we're talking about in our staff comments.
So I think it's better.
I think it's for the better.
And also, what has changed in this area,
is going from an overall city voting for the politicians to districts.
We've broken up the districts.
We have eight districts.
And the mayor is at large, so it sort of gives
a little more individual pressure for each of these districts so they all have their counseling.
Basically the ethnic breakdown is two blacks, one Mexican-American, and the other is a... Caucasian.
Caucasian, right.
They're all Caucasians, but you hate to say black.
But they're not .
OK. Generally, that's really the right kind of thing.
OK. Have those, what did you just call it, those districts, are they established on the same boundaries as the sectors for your planning?
OK.
The only reason that the boundaries of the sectors are generally made up from the same kind of .
neighborhood, census tracts areas, major elements that would make a major barrier.
It was more for a planning purpose than anything else.
Well, we've touched upon the ethnic influences.
Can you expand upon those influences on planning in the community?
The only thing I can, let's see.
Such as possibly the influx of, or the immigration of Mexicans or Asians in the early years.
Well, of course, yeah, we see a lot of that, but again, these are really more in the, what we call the port areas of the community, and generally it's just...
It hasn't been a major problem or anything, but you can see and there's a lot of feedback from the community that there's a difference going on.
You can see the changing time in the area in terms of the influx of this group, different ethnic groups.
But generally that's about it.
There hasn't been any major influence by them to develop a particular history or anything of this nature at this time.
So when people think of Fort Worth, they don't think of maybe like a little Italy or Chinatown or something like that?
It's mostly...
The only thing I can think of over the north side would be the Mexican-American side.
And what we call the southeast area, which is the black area of the community, but that's generally it.
Other than that, these new groups haven't had any influence at all as of yet.
They probably will.
And the only influence on planning would be the subsequent, maybe a different economic status in those areas or something?
Right.
Okay, not because of their beliefs or...
Right, right.
Okay.
How about the military influence, especially like with Carswell Air Force Base?
That's one of the major industries, Carswell, and also GD, General Dynamics, and they're one of the largest...
In part in the community and of course Bell Helicopter, which is, as it plans, it's not in for work, but it's in heavy influence also.
The military has had, I would say, in terms of development of the community, growth of the community.
There's been a problem with the Carswell Air Force Base, that is, with growth and the noise from the
jet planes and so forth that's causing problems.

It really has influenced our plan for that area in that we feel a lot of the areas that are hard of crest and are adjacent to the base, we generally see more of a, hopefully an industrial type use because of the noise factor and the residential use.
That's the plan.
OK. How about on the influence of the loop with 280?
Has that controlled growth at all?
Yeah.
And what we are seeing is that in terms of zoning requests, major influences around the major intersections of what we call the loop and also the east, west, north, south,

freeway system uh where these things converge is generally where we see a higher development intensity a lot of what we call g zones which is really high rise type development we see in those areas so what it's going to do which is good it's going to develop loads around those major intersections which over a period of time could become if the density of the community was to increase later years could be uh
Transportation, though, could be linked to each of those little nodes to the downtown area.
OK, how about with Texas Christian University?
Has that made any impact on the planning for the city?
No, it hasn't.
We've worked pretty well with TCU, and they've expanded their
university somewhat, and they do have to pay.

There is some problem there with the residential area, but we are working with the city, the citizens, and also with TCE to try to develop some kind of a system where they would have a master plan, and they wouldn't influence the area too much.
But that influence is there.
You can see that some problems wouldn't work.
OK.
The one that I wanted to bring up
The Texas West London Colleges, which is just part of some land out now, ETJ, it has been annexed.
They have a complete new campus in the area.
And the old campus is basically in an older part of the community called the Polytechnic area, which is a mixture of blacks and whites.
Now, that was the area that was generally white, but back in the 50s, you know, what they called a pipe fight.
People were moving out of the center city.
That was one of the areas that was really hidden, and a lot of people moved out of that area.
And so some of the blacks moved into there.
So now you have a black and white mixture, which there's no problem.
The problem is that with the new campus for TWC, the dilemma is what to do with the old campus.
And there have been some discussions in the papers about the Stephen F. Austin College having up here developing courses
to have what they call a window to the Metroplex, which will be good because it will hopefully keep the area a little more viable.
But that campus does influence that area, but not to a major extent.
You know what I'm saying?
A little in terms of commercial use, but other than that, it really doesn't.
All right.
Speaking of other inner city influences, how about the affluent area around colonial country club and all?
Does that have a major effect on your planning at all?
How did that area begin?
I can tell you generally how.
Well, I would say the way it began.
I'm just speculating, but I'm saying just the areas
that people would allow money to develop the area, and that's just the hard way it could be.
The other thing is,
There was, at one time, the west of the downtown called the Arlington Heights area.
At one time, it's called, it has a major street down there, it's called Camp Bowie Boulevard, which is very, historically very significant.
Actually, that area was where supposedly
It was called Camp Bull because that's where the camp was for the military back in the early days.
But the thing is that is one of the areas that has really came up in terms of cost of property and maybe so we started to
in place to be because it has access to the cultural district, it has good access to the major park system that we have, it has access to the river, you know.
So it has all these inputs on it and it really has
had a major impact in terms of the cost of the presidential unit down there.
But that's generally the only area.
OK. How have you considered the Trinity River in your planning?
Have there been any problems as far as flooding?
No.
They have a levee.
It's controlled by our local water control board.
It is used quite extensively by people who have biking trails along it and also have hiking trails.
It's used quite a bit for jogging and so forth.
It's really become a major element of the community and it's been utilized.
How about the influence of Dallas-Fort Worth Airport?
Has there been much of an impact on Fort Worth?
Yeah, I think generally the impact has been in terms of the people in the downtown hoping for future development.
There's been a major office development in the downtown.
I can't remember off the top of my head, I can't say how many square feet, but it's double the square footage that was here before 19...
So I think everybody's hoping or banking on the idea of the influence of the Dallas-Fort Worth airport that we'll have in the downtown in terms of the financial maintenance and audits area.
The problem with the city of Fort Worth is that we really don't have like a northeast section of the community.
That's different.
That begins to be made up of different cities.

We have one that's adjacent to Fort Worth, it's Hawthorne City, and then we have North Richland Hills, and then you have Bedford, Collierville, and then you have Euless, and then you have the airport.
Those, I would say if anybody has benefited, those communities between Fort Worth and the airport probably benefited more than we have.
But, you know, we would have, had we had this quadrant in here, I think it would have been a major influence.
Okay, where do you foresee growth in Fort Worth right now?
Well, right now, we see a heck of a lot of growth.
Actually, north, what we call them,
Northeast area, or what we call Summerfield area up here, part of Little Bay 20 and east of I-35.
There's a major development down here.
Okay, and so the growth is mainly to the north?
Okay, the other growth is in the southwest area, which is east of, I mean west of Little Bay.
of I-35 and south of Loop 820.
Generally, that's been the growth.
There's quite a number of proposals and zoning changes to the east, but one of the big influences here is going to be what we call the Fort Worth-Dallas Turnpike, which is I-30 going to Dallas.
getting access on two areas where there wasn't access previously.
So what that has caused is major changes in terms of zoning requests along that corridor going to Dow, so I wouldn't see a major development in that area in the future.
So the three areas would be what we call south of the Wedgwood,
and the Summerfields area, and what we call the Bentley Village area.
Okay, what would you say would be the reasons for the growth in the south of Wedgwood and the Ridgefield area?
The Wedgwood area, that's weird.
I can't understand.
There's no job market down there.
The only job market is...
There's a Carswell Air Force Base up here, but hell, it's a hell of a way to get up there.
But I just think it's just the area that people wanted to be down there.
I can't understand.
The open space.
There is an industrial development out along I-35, but there's nothing.
There's not that much to house all those people, so I don't really tell you where those people are going or where they're working.
In fact, it's really more of a problem because, again, we did our study on Southwest Freeway, and if anything, the road conditions are going to get worse before they ever get better.
If we ever see that Southwest Freeway coming along, we'll probably talk to anybody from seven to ten years from now.
And by that time, man, you're going to have real traffic problems there.
So I don't understand why would people want to go down there and live.
Now the other area, which is the Summerfields area, is a good area because you have good access to the freeway system.
Just driving time, I'm not saying getting out of your car and parking and walking to where you want to go, but driving time to downtown Fort Worth is, you know, 15 minutes, 20 minutes.
Maybe to Dallas downtown, and I'm saying just on a general day, I'm not saying during morning traffic, is no more than 40 minutes.
So convenience has caused that.
I think in course of development of the
the Dallas-Fort Worth Airport.
Also, there's Las Colinas, which is located adjacent to Dallas-Fort Worth.
It's going to be a big market for employment.
So that has spurred a lot of development over here.
That's why I can't see this development in Wedgwood.
I don't understand it.
I just don't understand how people want to move there.
If anything, it should either be all over here or even in the Meadowbrook area.
Now, the Meadowbrook area is changing, but it's not happening as fast as the other areas.
We are having a lot of important development moments.
what we call East Chase Parkway, which has just gotten access to I-30, and then we're going to have another one about a mile away, which would be Cook's Lane.
So those are two good access points.
And there are going to be some major changes in those areas in terms of the connection between Loop A-20 and I-30.
So now you can't get from I-30 to Loop A-20 without...
coming off the freeway and going on the French Road and then coming back and then coming home.
So it's a real hassle.
Do you foresee a continuation of the loop?
Yeah.
Down to about this, you're talking about?
Yes.
All the way down to 35.
This is tied back like this.
You mean the southwest freeway you're talking about?
Yes.
Where are they pointing at?
Right there.
Oh, OK.
No, it'll just come back this way.
It'll come back this way.
So you get a complete loop here.
All right.
One other big influence.
In reference to transportation, there might be also another development going on in that we would probably like to do, and we're going to look at this in our district planning,

try to tie in with the loop off of, now this would be a long range plan, but loop 635 here that ties in with our loop 820, we might want to try to tie in with that loop, which is called North Dallas, where you have all the gallery and all the traffic problems.
What's happening is if we tie in with this 635, we could bring that over and tie back in to our loop 820.
So in essence, you could have access, you know,
to the north side of Dallas-Wilworth plus also the north side of, I mean, Dallas-Wilworth Airport plus the north side of Dallas.
Who would be responsible for forming a plan like that?
We would be.
The North Texas Council of Governments?
We would be working with them.
We'd develop a plan for our ETJ area.
We'd try to work with all these other different municipalities and try to develop a corridor to these so we could hopefully
implement that plan for the future.
So there is no area-wide planning agency that would consider all of these regional aspects?
All right.
What has been Fort Worth's relationship, since you've been here, with the city of Dallas?
Traditionally, there's been a rivalry.
Is that still existent?
No.
In fact, we just got Clark Grant, or in the process of getting Grant, to develop the railroad.
There's a railroad going from downtown Fort Worth to Dallas.
I'm trying to remember what the name was.
You can talk to my transportation plan.
Or the railroad, so we'd have access from downtown Fort Worth to downtown Dallas.
Via railroad.
Via railroad, and that, I'm trying to think of the name of it.
I don't know.
So that's just a plan on... Well, no, it's going to, it'll happen.
I mean, initially we're buying up the railroad.
I mean, just buying up the right-of-way.
Will that be a railroad for transportation of the public?
Yeah, a commuter.
